Pharmacology of heart rate/rhythm 

Sunday, April 30, 2017 

12:44 PM 

G-Protein coupled receptors (GPCR) 

-These are receptors found only in eukaryotes 

-Largest known class of membrane receptors (Humans have over 1000 known types of GPCRs) 

-Each is a very unique membrane receptor and is the target of up to 50% of modern drugs 

-Things that bind include light-sensitive compounds, odors, pheromones, hormones, neurotransmitters 

-Regulate immune system, growth, sense of smell, taste, vision, behaviour, mood (includes serotonin and dopamine) 

 

Structure of GPCR 

-Very uniquely has 7 transmembrane alpha helices  

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

-GPCRs are coupled with G-proteins, and interact with them. G-proteins are special proteins which have the ability to bind Guanosine triphosphate and Guanosine diphosphate (GTP and GDP). Some G-proteins are small with only a single subunit. However, all the G-proteins associated with GPCRs are heterotrimeric (meaning they have 3 different subunits). These 3 subunits are the alpha, beta and gamma subunits. 

 

In the inactive state, the GPCR binds GDP to the alpha subunit. When a ligand binds to the receptor, the GPCR undergoes a conformational change. Following the conformational change, the alpha subunit exchanges the GDP for GTP. When GTP is bound to the alpha subunit, the alpha subunit dissociates from the G-protein, from the beta/gamma dimer. The alpha subunit will find a different protein in the bilayer and interact with it. Both the alpha subunit and the beta/gamma dimer can interact with other proteins to relay messages and regulate the protein's function.  

 

Target proteins can be enzymes that produce second messengers, or ion channels that also let ions as second messengers. Resultantly, activity can either be stimulated or inhibited. 

 

To deactivate the GPCR 

GTP is hydrolysed to GDP, losing a phosphate through hydrolysis. Once this happens, everything goes back to normal and the ligand leaves. The hydrolysis of GTP can be regulated, such as via the RGS (Regulation of G-protein signaling) protein. Hydrolysis can also occur on its own.  

 

Example of GPCR function 

Adrenaline ligand binds to the adrenergic receptor eg Beta-1-adrenoreceptor (a GPCR), causing it to undergo a conformational change. The alpha subunit exchanges GDP for GTP, dissociating from the rest of the G-protein and seeking out the adenylate cyclase protein. The adenylate cyclase is activated, taking ATP and removing two phosphates to produce Cyclic Adenosine Monophosphate (cAMP). The cAMP molecule is a 2nd messenger, telling the cell to undergo other actions such as functions to increase heart rate, dilate skeletal blood vessels, and break down glycogen to glucose. 

 

In particular, the cAMP activates Protein Kinase A (PKA) which phosphorylates calcium channels, increase Ca2+ influx thereby increasing the force of muscle contraction. There is an increased sensitivity of contractile machinery to Ca2+. Ca2+ capture by the sarcoplasmic reticulum is also facilitated for later response to action potentials. The increase in heart rate results from an increased slope of the pacemaker potential, and increased Ca2+ entry which increases automaticity.  

 

Parasympathetic interaction with the heart 

-Mediated by M2 muscarinic receptors 

-Abundant in nodal and atrial tissue but sparse in the ventricles 

ACH is negatively coupled to adenylate cyclase, decreasing cAMP levels. This inhibits the opening of Ca2+ channels and reduces Ca2+ currents. K+ channels are opened to increase K+ efflux, with a hyperpolarising current that opposes the inward pacemaker current. Heart rate is slowed, and automaticity is reduced. Decreased Ca2+ inhibits AV conduction.  

 

Explain the relationship between the targets of the following drug classes and the control of heart rate (including the effect on action potentials at relevant sites in the heart) 

 

-Sodium channel blockers 

These increase the action potential threshold for depolarisation, and increases the time taken in phase 0. They only block fast sodium channels. This decreases automaticity. They decrease the plateau phase and reduce conduction velocity. These drugs are split into 3 classes. 

-Beta blockers 

Beta-adrenergic receptor antagonists are the group of "-olol" drugs. They prevent binding of adrenaline/noradrenaline to beta-adrenergic receptors, therefore decreasing the frequency of SA and AV node firing. This decreases heart rate.  

 

-Potassium blockers 

The blockage of potassium efflux channels lengthens phase 3, thereby increasing the refractory period. These often block sodium channels too. 

 

-Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers 

These block voltage-sensitive L-type calcium channels. Non-DHP calcium channel blockers work at the SA and the AV nodes. (DHP calcium channel blockers work at the blood vessels). Non-DHP calcium channel blockers slow the rise of phase 0 in the nodal action potential. This slows conduction velocity through the AV node, prolonging repolarisation of the AV node.  

 

-Digoxin (Type of cardiac glycoside) 

These increase the force of contraction, and cause cardiac slowing and a reduced rate of conduction through the AV node due to increased vagal activity. Glycosides inhibit the sodium/potassium pump. A rise in sodium influx causes a decrease in NCX function, leading to a buildup of calcium in the cell. This increases contraction force.
